# Pattern Evaluation (LCP-UML-4)

| Pattern | Participants (classes/records) | Abstract vs. Concrete | Notes |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| MVC Controller | Controllers/*Controller | Concrete controllers | Attribute-routed WebAPI controllers orchestrate requests and return DTO/entity results. |
| Dependency Injection / IoC | Program.cs, FleetDbContext injected into controllers | N/A (framework service) | ASP.NET Core DI container wires DbContext into controllers; promotes ctor injection. |
| DTO (Data Transfer Object) | DTOs/*Dto records | Concrete records | Request/response contracts separate from EF entities, limiting over-posting. |
| Unit of Work + Repository (via EF Core DbContext/DbSet) | FleetDbContext, DbSet<T> sets | Concrete DbContext; DbSet<T> repositories | SaveChanges/transactions wrap multiple changes; DbSet<T> provides repository-like access without custom abstraction. |
| Optimistic Concurrency Token | BaseEntity.RowVersion; checks in Vehicles/RoutePlans/ChargingStations controllers | Abstract base + concrete controllers | RowVersion bytes compared before updates; prevents ghost writes and stale updates. |
| Abstract Base Entity | BaseEntity | Abstract | Centralizes Id, RowVersion, LockToken for all domain entities. |

Totals & Metrics
- Total classes scanned: 18 (controllers, models, DbContext, BaseEntity).
- Patterns found: 6
- Pattern density: 6 / 18 = **0.33**

Abstract / Interface Types
- Abstract: BaseEntity
- Interfaces: none
- Concrete classes: FleetDbContext; 8 controllers; 8 domain/entity models.
- Concrete records (DTOs): 13 request/response shapes.

Decoupling & SOLID Grade: **B-**
- 👍 Separation of API contracts (DTOs) from EF entities; use of DI and concurrency tokens improves SRP and correctness.
- 👎 Controllers contain business logic and data access directly; no repository/service interfaces, so high coupling to EF Core and poor testability (hurts D/I and O/C). No domain services to encapsulate transactions or policies.
- 🔧 Suggested improvements: introduce application services or repositories behind interfaces; move transaction/concurrency workflows out of controllers; add interface-based abstractions for DbContext to aid testing; consider domain events/observers for side effects.
